<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-289-244  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 289 244.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  March 8 1990 n1204 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big boss is watching you. (as computer systems become more vitalto businesses, scrutiny of data processing personnel becomes moreintense) (includes a related article examining the extent andnature of employee computer crime)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tilley, Leslie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Employers, who once based hiring choices on resumes, past employerreferences, and managerial evaluation, are beginning to gatherinformation on prospective and current employees' politicaltendencies and after-hours activities, often without the knowledgeof the individual being investigated.andP;  The reason for thisscrutiny is the vulnerability of computer systems to damage orfraudulent use by employees.andP;  A study by the European SecurityForum estimates losses from computer failures and/or deliberateaction to be close to 1 billion pounds sterling, and 80 percent ofcomputer crime is committed by employees.andP;  Since it is extremelydifficult to track down, let alone win a conviction againstcomputer criminals, the best defensive measure is prevention.andO;Civil libertarians are calling into question some of the methodsbeing used to spot potential computer security risks, includingthe use of private investigators who may have a vested interest infinding damaging information on an individual in order to ensuretheir own further employment by the firm.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimesSecurityEDP PersonnelEmploymentHiringInvestigationsPolitical Issues.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>